I often think that Millennials might be the last generation capable of purely appreciating art and forming connections with artists. They don't have the pressure to examine everything through a critical, biased lens.
We grew up during the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of pop culture, but this collective awareness has since disappeared.
Back then, we could immerse ourselves in content without worrying about its origins, because tracing sources was not easy in that era.
We revered these artists without any reason to question this reverence. Thus, we established a "parasocial relationship" with them, viewing it as an essential part of our lives.
This also explains why we are so obsessed with nostalgia.
When the show "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I would gather every Thursday to watch it together while eating pizza.
This is vastly different from our current experience of watching shows on streaming platforms. Streaming services usually release all 12 episodes at once, and everyone watches them at their own pace, posting discussions on social media with "spoiler warnings" or simply communicating within specific groups.
Unconsciously, we all long for that sense of collective belonging that connected everyone.
It's precisely this nostalgia that drives us to rewatch shows like "The Office" or movies like "The Daily Show," whose unforgettable lines spread online like memes.
We quote these classic lines from the works and assume most people will understand them.
Nowadays, even if something goes viral online, we can't assume everyone has seen it.
With the explosion of information, there are simply too many things demanding our attention to ever simplify... Do we still have a chance to escape this state of information overload?
We keep discovering new media and new artists, only to find out that they are either notorious sexual predators or stubborn bigots full of prejudices, and this cycle is exhausting.
On one hand, we indulge in nostalgia, but on the other hand, we have to admit that the people who created the artworks we love may have serious moral flaws, and this contradictory心理 leaves us feeling confused and helpless.
We will be more cautious in forming "pseudo-social relationships" with artists.
We are gradually realizing that if one wants to gain wealth and power, it is difficult to ensure that one will not harm or exploit others.
Since the collective consciousness of the media no longer exists, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, there are still some people who stubbornly insist on elevating others to a pedestal, only to act shocked when their idols fall.
We are living in an era of transformation, and I urgently want to know where we are heading.
